ement for peace and security in different countries across the globe and in different types and phases of conflict and violence, including both conflict-affected and relatively peaceful societies. Chapter contributors, young peacebuilders, and seasoned scholars and practitioners alike propose ways to support youth’s agency and facilitate their meaningful participation in decision-making. The chapters are organized around five broad thematic issues that correspond to the 5 Pillars of Action identified by UN Security Council Resolution 2250. Lessons learned are intended to inform the global youth, peace, and security agenda so that it better responds to on-the-ground realities, hence promoting more sustainable and inclusive approaches to long-lasting peace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aYouth and peace. 0aYouth in peace-building. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apeace, youth, young people, national security, violent conflict, conflict, United Nations Security Council Resolution 2250, United Nations, UN, 2015, human security, environmentally secure.1 aAltiok, Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAltiok, Ali.1 aAtuhaire, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtuhaire, Grace.1 aBishop, Victoria R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBishop, Victoria.1 aBudur, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBudur, Diana.1 aEnsor, Marisa O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnsor, Marisa O., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIzzi, Valeria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIzzi, Valeria.1 aKhalid, Nasrat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a